Ju-seok)&nbsp;\u2013 2019\n\n{{col-2-of-4}}\n\n'''All-Star Game selections'''\n*Bumper (Park Sang-beom)&nbsp;\u2013 2019\n*Haksal (Kim Hyo-jong)&nbsp;\u2013 2019\n*SLIME (Kim Seong-jun)&nbsp;\u2013 2019\n*Twilight (Lee Ju-seok)&nbsp;\u2013 2019\n\n'''All-Star Game head coaches'''\n*paJion (Hwang Ji-sub)&nbsp;\u2013 2019\n\n{{col-3-of-4}}\n{{col-4-of-4}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Vancouver Titans}}\n* {{Official website|https://vancouvertitans.gg/}}\n\n{{Vancouver Titans}}\n{{Overwatch League}}\n\n[[Category:Overwatch League teams]]\n[[Category:Esports teams established in 2018]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Esports teams based in Canada]]\n[[Category:Vancouver Titans| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the [[Overwatch League]] team|the professional basketball team which was named the Vancouver Titans from 2008 to 2009|BC Titans}}\n{{short description|Canadian professional esports team}}\n{{Infobox sports team\n| name = Vancouver Titans\n| logo = Vancouver Titans logo.svg\n| upright = .85\n| alt = The logo for the Vancouver Titans features a [[Sasquatch]] with a 'V' in the nose and a mountain range on the top of its head.\n| founded = September 7, 2018\n| current = 2020 Vancouver Titans season\n| current_icon = Esports\n| league = [[Overwatch League]]\n| conference = Pacific\n| division = West\n| history = '''Vancouver Titans'''<br />(2018\u2013present)\n| city = [[Vancouver]], [[Canada]]\n| arena = [[Rogers Arena]]\n| colors = {{color box|#0a226c}} {{color box|#2fb228}} {{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n| owner = [[Canucks Sports & Entertainment]]\n| gm = \n| coach = Hwang \"paJion\" Ji-sub\n| championships = \n| uniforms = Vancouver Titans Jersey.svg\n| main_sponsor = <!-- Main sponsor should only contain the team's 1 match jersey sponsor -->\n| website = {{Official website|https://vancouvertitans.gg/}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Vancouver Titans''' is a professional [[Overwatch (video game)#Professional competition|''Overwatch'' esports]] team based in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada. The Titans compete in the [[Overwatch League]] (OWL) as a member of the league's Pacific West Division.\n\nFounded in 2018, the Vancouver Titans began play as one of eight [[expansion team]]s in 2019 and is one of two professional ''Overwatch teams'' in [[Canada]] (the other, [[Toronto Defiant]]). The team is owned by [[Canucks Sports & Entertainment]], owners of the [[Vancouver Canucks]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) and the [[Vancouver Warriors]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL), and will play their home matches at [[Rogers Arena]], which is also owned by Canucks Sports & Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Plana |first1=Vincent |title=Details revealed about Rogers Arena-hosted live esports matches |url=https://dailyhive.com/vancouver/vancouver-titans-esports-rogers-arena |accessdate=October 11, 2019 |work=Daily Hive |date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHwang \"paJion\" Ji-sub was appointed the team's first head coach and, in his first season, guided Vancouver to three stage playoff appearances, including one stage championship, a Pacific Division (now the Pacific Conference) title, and the [[2019 Overwatch League Grand Finals|2019 Grand Finals]], where the team lost to the [[San Francisco Shock]].\n\n== History ==\n=== OWL expansion ===\nOn September 7, 2018, [[Activision Blizzard]] announced that [[National Hockey League|NHL]]'s [[Vancouver Canucks]] ownership [[Francesco Aquilini|Aquilini Group]] had purchased a slot for the Vancouver-based franchise for a reported $30 million to $60 million.<ref name=\"ESPN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/24600366/overwatch-league-reveals-toronto-paris-four-other-new-franchises|title=Overwatch League reveals Toronto, Paris, and four other new franchises|last=Rand|first=Emily|work=[[ESPN]]|date=September 7, 2018|accessdate=November 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Founded\">{{Cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/the-overwatch-leagues-8-new-teams-are-preparing-for-season-two|title=It\u2019s official: All 8 new teams coming to Overwatch League have been revealed|last=Carpenter|first=Nicole|date=September 7, 2018|website=Dot Esports|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 11, 2018}}</ref> \"Esports has seen extraordinary success and continues to be one of the fastest growing industries in the world,\" said Aquilini Group managing director Francesco Aquilini in a statement. \"We can't wait to launch the team in Vancouver.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Black |first1=Matthew |last2=Haberstroh |first2=Max |title=Canucks owners bring pro esports team to Vancouver |date=September 7, 2018 |work=CBC News |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/vancouver-canucks-esports-1.4813927 |access-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref> On October 18, the team announced they had partnered with Canadian esports organization [[Luminosity Gaming]] to add esports expertise to the organization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/25016693|title=Vancouver Overwatch team partners with Luminosity Gaming|date=2018-10-18|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\nOn December 1, a video revealed the Vancouver Titans' brand during the second intermission of a Vancouver Canucks game, concluding with \"Today, we release the Titans.\" The team also announced that it had signed all eight members of the Korean Contenders Champions [[RunAway]] and Hwang \"paJion\" Ji-sub as the team's head coach.<ref name=brandreveal>{{cite news |agency=Reuters |title=Overwatch: Vancouver Titans reveal branding, roster |date=December 1, 2018 |work=ESPN |url=http://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/page/overwatchvancouvertitans/overwatch-league-vancouver-titans-reveal-branding-roster |access-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Inaugural season ===\n{{main|2019 Vancouver Titans season}}\n[[File:Haksal.jpg|thumb|left|upright=.7|[[Haksal]] won the 2019 OWL Rookie of the Year award.]]\nVancouver started the season with a 4\u20130 sweep over the [[Shanghai Dragons]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Fossett |first=Wyatt |title=Vancouver Titans win their Overwatch League debut |date=February 17, 2019 |work=Daily Hive |url=https://dailyhive.com/vancouver/vancouver-titans-overwatch-league-debut |access-date=June 20, 2019}}</ref> The team ended Stage 1 with a perfect 7\u20130 record and went on to win the Stage 1 Finals against the Shock.<ref name=\"S1 Finals\">{{cite news |last=Richardson |first=Liz |title=Vancouver Titans are the Overwatch League stage one champions |work=Dot Esports |date=March 24, 2019 |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/vancouver-titans-overwatch-league-stage-one-champions |access-date=September 18, 2019}}</ref> The Titans posted another perfect 7\u20130 record in Stage 2; however, they lost in the Stage 2 Finals against the Shock, which ended their Overwatch League record 19-game win streak (including playoffs).<ref name=\"S2 Finals\">{{cite news |last=Polacek |first=Scott |title=Overwatch League 2019 Stage 2 Finals: Shock's Top Plays, Prize Money |work=Bleacher Report |date=May 12, 2019 |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2835895-overwatch-league-2019-stage-2-finals-shocks-top-plays-prize-money |access-date=June 20, 2019}}</ref> The team continued their regular season dominance by winning an Overwatch League record 19 consecutive games that was not snapped until in June 23, when the [[Los Angeles Valiant]] defeated the Titans.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fossett |first1=Wyatt |title=LA Valiant End Vancouver Titans' 19-Game OWL Winning Streak |url=https://www.twingalaxies.com/feed_details.php/5663/la-valiant-end-vancouver-titans-19-game-owl-winning-streak/24 |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |work=Twin Galaxies |date=June 23, 2019}}</ref> While they qualified for the Stage 3 playoffs, Vancouver was defeated by the [[Shanghai Dragons]] in the semifinals round.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Heinisch |first1=Sascha |title=Shanghai Dragons unexpectedly make Stage 3 playoff finals |url=https://upcomer.com/overwatch/story/1426239/shanghai-dragons-upset-vancouver-titans-owl-stage-3-playoffs |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |work=Upcomer |date=July 14, 2019}}</ref> The Titans lost two more times in the regular season, against the [[Washington Justice]] and San Francisco Shock, to end the regular season with a league-best 25\u20133 record and the top seed in the season playoffs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patterson |first1=Calum |title=How to watch Overwatch League Season 2 playoffs - Streams, schedule, results |url=https://www.dexerto.com/overwatch/how-to-watch-overwatch-league-season-2-playoffs-stream-schedule-results-976163 |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |work=Dexerto |date=September 1, 2019}}</ref> [[Kim \"Haksal\" Hyo-jong]] and Lee \"Twilight\" Ju-seok were awarded the Role Star commendation for DPS and support, respectively;<ref name=\"Role Star\">{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Liz |title=Overwatch League reveals Role Stars awards |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/overwatch-league-reveals-role-stars-awards |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=August 31, 2019}}</ref> Haksal was also named the OWL Rookie of the year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Liz |title=Haksal is Overwatch League\u2019s Rookie of the Year |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/haksal-is-overwatch-leagues-rookie-of-the-year |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=September 5, 2019}}</ref> Twilight and tank Choi \"Jjanu\" Hyeon-woo were finalists for the league's most valuable player award, but the Shock's [[Jay \"sinatraa\" Won]] won the award.<ref name=\"MVP\">{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Liz |title=San Francisco Shock\u2019s Sinatraa wins 2019 Overwatch League MVP award |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/san-francisco-shocks-sinatraa-wins-2019-overwatch-league-mvp-award |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nVancouver faced the eighth-seeded [[Seoul Dynasty]] in the first round of the playoffs, winning 4\u20132 after claiming three straight map victories.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gladiators, Titans win on Day 1 of Overwatch League playoffs |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27547940/gladiators-titans-win-day-1-overwatch-league-playoffs |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |work=ESPN |agency=Reuters |date=September 6, 2019}}</ref> Advancing to the first round of the winners bracket, the team took down the fifth-seeded [[Los Angeles Gladiators]] by a 4\u20132 score.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Liz |title=Vancouver Titans and New York Excelsior advance in the Overwatch League postseason |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/vancouver-titans-and-new-york-excelsior-advance-in-the-overwatch-league-postseason |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=September 8, 2019}}</ref> In the Winners' Finals, Vancouver faced the [[New York Excelsior]]; the match went to seven maps, as the two teams traded map wins throughout. The Titans came out on top with a 4\u20133 victory to advance to the [[2019 Overwatch League Grand Finals|Grand Finals]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hoskins |first1=Ryan |title=Vancouver Titans to Advance to OWL Grand Finals |url=https://www.hotspawn.com/vancouver-titans-to-advance-to-owl-grand-finals/ |accessdate=September 20, 2019 |work=Hotspawn |date=September 14, 2019}}</ref> The Titans season came to an end short, as they were swept 0\u20134 by the Shock in the Grand Finals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shock sweep Titans in Overwatch League final |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/27729415/how-shock-swept-titans-overwatch-league-grand-final |accessdate=September 30, 2019 |work=ESPN |agency=Reuters |date=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, the Vancouver Titans announced the departures of Park \u201cBumper\u201d Sang-beom, Dong-eun \"Hooreg\" Lee, Jung-keun \"Rapel\" Kim, and Jang-hyeon \"TiZi\" Hwang.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Richardson |first1=Liz |title=Vancouver Titans part ways with Hooreg |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/vancouver-titans-part-ways-with-hooreg/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Dot Esports |date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 season ===\n{{main|2020 Vancouver Titans season}}\nOn November 27th, 2019, the Vancouver Titans announced the new additions to the roster including Baek \u201cFissure\u201d Chan-hyung and Ryu \u201cRyujehong\u201d Je-hong.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Howard |first1=Brian |title=Vancouver Titans Add Ryujehong to Roster |url=https://www.hotspawn.com/vancouver-titans-add-ryujehong-to-roster/ |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=Hotspawn |date=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2020 season, the Overwatch League adopted the home/away format, where teams play at their home arenas called \u201chomestands\u201d.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Webster |first1=Andrew |title=Blizzard explains how home and away games will work in the Overwatch League |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/7/16/20694642/blizzard-overwatch-league-home-away-games-esports-2020 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=The Verge |date=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Titans first homestand titled \u201cForce Fest: Homecoming\u201d will be at the Rogers Arena on May 16th and 17th, 2020. The second Vancouver Titans homestand will take place on July 4th and 5th, 2020 with details yet to be announced.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Plana |first1=Vincent |title=Here's how much it will cost to watch Vancouver's pro esports team live at Rogers Arena |url=https://dailyhive.com/vancouver/vancouver-titans-homestand-rogers-arena-tickets |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=The Daily Hive |date=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Team identity ==\nOn December 1, 2018, the Aquilini Group officially unveiled the Vancouver Titans brand. The name ''Titans'' is \"indicative of the traits associated with the [[Sasquatch]] \u2013 a powerful, imposing, and mythical being.\" The logo features the [[Pacific Northwest]] folklore figure with a 'V' in the nose and a mountain range on the top of its head in the team's colours of blue, green, and white. The colours represent the greenery that surrounds the [[Pacific Ocean]] in the Vancouver area and are similar of that of the [[Vancouver Canucks]]' official colours. \"In choosing our identity we wanted to introduce a team that would resonate with fans in the Pacific Northwest,\" Aquilini Group managing editor Francesco Aquilini said in a statement. \"With a local feel and an experienced, skilled team, we are ready and can't wait to have the Titans compete at the highest level in esports.\"<ref name=brandreveal /><ref>{{cite news |title=Introducing the Vancouver Titans: The New Overwatch League Team Competing in the 2019 Season |date=December 3, 2018 |work=Gamasutra |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/332016/INTRODUCING_THE_VANCOUVER_TITANS_THE_NEW_OVERWATCH_LEAGUE_TEAM_COMPETING_IN_THE_2019_SEASON_nbsp.php |access-date=March 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Partnerships ==\n=== 2019 season ===\nDuring the 2019 season, the Vancouver Titans announced partnerships with convenience store chain Circle K, recycling company Encorp, consumer electronics retailer Best Buy, and brewing company Bud Light. On August 7th, 2019, the Vancouver Titans announced a partnership with Circle K on limited edition Froster Cups. The Froster cups featured players Hyojong \u201cHaksal\u201d Kim, Juseok \u201cTwilight\u201d Lee, Minsoo \u201cSeoMinSoo\u201d Seo, and Sangbeom \u201cBumper\u201d Park.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Strickland |first1=Will |title=Vancouver Titans collectible cups available at Circle K |url=https://dotesports.com/news/vancouver-titans-circle-k/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Hotspawn |date=August 8, 2019}}</ref>This partnership was the first of its kind for Canada with an esports team working with a national convenience store. In September 2019, Bud Light announced on Twitter that commemorative Bud Light cans will be coming to Vancouver to celebrate the Vancouver Titans making the Grand Finals of the Overwatch League.{{Cite tweet |user=BudLightCA |number=1178416556109381632 |date = 29 September 2019 |title=gg @VancouverTitans. Commemorative can on the way for an epic 1st season. Raising one to you! #ForceOfNature #OWL2019 #OWLGrandFinals}}On November 14th, 2020, Bud Light announced that the commemorative cans will be available for a limited time at the 1st Avenue Liquor store in Vancouver, BC, Canada on Friday, November 15th,2019.{{Cite tweet |user=BudLightCA |number=1195068887563472896 |date = 14 November 2019 |title=HEY @VANCOUVERTITANS FANS! CANS WILL BE AVAILABLE THIS SATURDAY AT 1ST AVENUE LIQUOR STORE (1st Ave & Renfrew) LIMITED RUN \u2013 SO MOVE LIKE GENJI. #ForceOfNature}}\n\n=== 2020 season ===\nOn January 14, 2020, the Vancouver Titans announced a multi-year partnership with gaming chair and desk manufacturer Arozzi North America.<ref>{{cite news |last1=De Vera |first1=Alfred |title=TITANS ANNOUNCE MULTI-YEAR PARTNERSHIP WITH AROZZI NORTH AMERICA |url=https://titans.overwatchleague.com/en-us/news/arozzi-partnership/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Titans Overwatch League |date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn February 21, 2020, the Vancouver Titans announced a partnership with Adamas Esports Training + Performance. Adamas Esports Training + Performance is located inside of Fortius Sport & Health in Burnaby, BC and the official home of the Vancouver Titans during the 2020 season of the Overwatch League.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Plana |first1=Vincent |title=Vancouver Titans reveal where they'll live while in the city (PHOTOS) |url=https://dailyhive.com/vancouver/vancouver-titans-fortius-sport-health-burnaby-bc/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Daily Hive Offside Vancouver |date=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n== Personnel ==\n=== Current roster ===\n{{Vancouver Titans roster}}\n\n=== Head coaches ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center